onseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Low amplitude pulses during sleep","High amplitude pulses throughout the day","Continuous secretion without pulsatility","High amplitude pulses during sleep only","Complete absence of secretion"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring the pre-pubertal period, \u003Cstrong\u003Elow amplitude pulses of luteinising hormone occur during sleep\u003C/strong\u003E. This represents an early stage of hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal axis maturation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh amplitude pulses throughout the day\u003C/strong\u003E - This pattern is characteristic of puberty, not the pre-pubertal period\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuous secretion without pulsatility\u003C/strong\u003E - LH is always secreted in a pulsatile manner\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh amplitude pulses during sleep only\u003C/strong\u003E - Pre-pubertal pulses are low, not high amplitude\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete absence of secretion\u003C/strong\u003E - Some LH secretion occurs even before puberty\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs puberty approaches, both the amplitude and frequency of LH pulses increase, eventually extending into waking hours. This change in secretion pattern is one of the earliest hormonal signs of pubertal onset.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Luteinizing hormone secretion shows characteristic patterns that change from infancy through puberty.","Pre-pubertal children have low amplitude pulses of luteinizing hormone that occur primarily during sleep.","The amplitude and frequency of luteinizing hormone pulses increase significantly during puberty."],"references":["Micangeli G, Paparella R, 